SIMPLE: thou
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: thou
<hw>thou</hw> <pr>(⟦th⟧ou)</pr>, <pos>pron.</pos>
<nmorph>[<pos>Sing.</pos>: <pos>nom.</pos> <decf>Thou</decf>;
<pos>poss.</pos> <decf>Thy</decf> <pr>(⟦th⟧⟦imac⟧)</pr> or
<decf>Thine</decf> <pr>(⟦th⟧⟦imac⟧n)</pr>; <pos>obj.</pos>
<decf>Thee</decf> <pr>(⟦th⟧⟦emac⟧)</pr>. <pos>Pl.</pos>: <pos>nom.</pos>
<decf>You</decf> <pr>(y⟦oomac⟧)</pr>; <pos>poss.</pos> <decf>Your</decf>
<pr>(y⟦oomac⟧r)</pr> or <decf>Yours</decf> <pr>(y⟦oomac⟧rz)</pr>;
<pos>obj.</pos> <decf>You</decf>.]</nmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>thou</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧u</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦edh⟧⟦umac⟧</ets>, <ets>⟦edh⟧u</ets>; akin
to OS. & OFries. <ets>thu</ets>, G., Dan. & Sw. <ets>du</ets>, Icel.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧⟦umac⟧</ets>, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧u</ets>, Russ.
<ets>tui</ets>, Ir. & Gael. <ets>tu</ets>, W. <ets>ti</ets>, L.
<ets>tu</ets>, Gr. <grk>sy`</grk>, Dor. <ets><grk>ty`</grk></ets>, Skr.
<ets>tvam</ets>. ⟦root⟧185. Cf. <er>Thee</er>, <er>Thine</er>, <er>Te
Deum</er>.]</ety> <def>The second personal pronoun, in the singular
number, denoting the person addressed; thyself; the pronoun which is
used in addressing persons in the solemn or poetical style.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Art <qex>thou</qex> he that should come?</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xi.
3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧In Old English, generally, <xex>thou</xex> is the
language of a lord to a servant, of an equal to an equal, and expresses
also companionship, love, permission, defiance, scorn, threatening:
whilst <xex>ye</xex> is the language of a servant to a lord, and of
compliment, and further expresses honor, submission, or
entreaty.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Skeat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Thou</xex> is now sometimes used by the Friends, or
Quakers, in familiar discourse, though most of them corruptly say
<xex>thee</xex> instead of <xex>thou</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thou</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Thou
<hw>Thou</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To address as <xex>thou</xex>, esp.
to do so in order to treat with insolent familiarity or
contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thou <qex>thouest</qex> him some thrice, it shall not be
amiss.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thou</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Thou
<hw>Thou</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To use the words <xex>thou</xex>
and <xex>thee</xex> in discourse after the manner of the Friends.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Though</ent>⟦br⟧
